<paragraph blockId="11.[497,818,1163,1222]" box="[497,818,1197,1222]" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">
<heading box="[497,818,1197,1222]" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431" reason="5">
<figureCitation box="[497,606,1197,1222]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="2.[160,225,1557,1580]" captionTargetBox="[164,1152,691,1526]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[163,1153,690,1526]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figure 1. Map showing distributions of species surveyed in the Kathmandu Valley: circles = amphibians, squares = reptiles. Colours are defined as follows, amphibians: dark blue = Duttaphrynus melanostictus, purple = Nanorana liebigii, yellow = Fejervarya syhadrensis, light green = Hoplobatrachus tigerinus, dark green = Euphlyctis cyanophylyctis, orange = Megophrys (Xenophrys) zhangi, red = Microhyla ornata. Reptiles: light purple = Calotes versicolor, light blue = Hemidactylus platyurus, dark blue = Hemidactylus frenatus, dark purple = Herpetoreas platyceps." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3670116" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3670116/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">Figures 1</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[670,686,1197,1222]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="8.[160,225,998,1021]" captionTargetBox="[354,962,142,966]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[354,962,142,966]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 3. Additional amphibian species observed during this survey. (a) Hoplobatrachus tigerinus, (b) Hoplobatrachus tigerinus, (c) Euphlyctis cyanophylyctis, (d) male Megophrys zhangi, (e) female (left) and male (right) of Megophrys zhangi, (f) tadpole of Megophrys zhangi, (g) male Megophrys zhangi calling on artificial substrate near water feature, (h) Microhyla ornata." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3670120" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3670120/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">3</figureCitation>
(h); 
<tableCitation box="[731,818,1197,1222]" captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="4.[160,216,142,165]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Table 2. Counts and locality information for all species encountered during this survey of the Kathmandu Valley, Nepal." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/EDA6A6DEE73EFFAB0EC276DBFE20E3FC" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431" tableUuid="EDA6A6DEE73EFFAB0EC276DBFE20E3FC">Table 2</tableCitation>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[160,761,1250,1274]" box="[160,761,1250,1274]" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">
<emphasis box="[160,389,1250,1274]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">specimens examined</emphasis>
: CMDN-A 47, 138 
<emphasis box="[591,604,1250,1274]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">–</emphasis>
139, 149 
<emphasis box="[701,714,1250,1274]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">–</emphasis>
150.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[160,1156,1296,1354]" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">
<emphasis box="[160,485,1296,1320]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">Distribution in the KTM Valley</emphasis>
: Encountered in Lalitpur and Shreshnaryan, although 
<bibRefCitation author="Aryal PC &amp; Kharel SC &amp; Bhurtel BP &amp; Paudel EN &amp; Dhamala MK &amp; Rijal B &amp; Thapa A" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431" pagination="1 - 3" refId="ref6442" refString="Aryal PC, Kharel SC, Bhurtel BP, Paudel EN, Dhamala MK, Rijal B, Thapa A. 2013. An amphibian survey in Kathmandu Valley. Nepal. Biodiv. Cons. Efforts Nepal. 3: 1 - 3." type="journal article" year="2013">Aryal et al. (2013)</bibRefCitation>
also encountered the species in north-western KTM Valley.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[160,1156,1376,1712]" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">
<emphasis box="[160,255,1376,1400]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">Remarks</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tschudi" authorityYear="1838" box="[273,383,1376,1400]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Microhyla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[273,383,1376,1400]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">Microhyla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were found at four sites around ponds or wetlands (
<figureCitation box="[1042,1142,1376,1400]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="2.[160,225,1557,1580]" captionTargetBox="[164,1152,691,1526]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[163,1153,690,1526]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figure 1. Map showing distributions of species surveyed in the Kathmandu Valley: circles = amphibians, squares = reptiles. Colours are defined as follows, amphibians: dark blue = Duttaphrynus melanostictus, purple = Nanorana liebigii, yellow = Fejervarya syhadrensis, light green = Hoplobatrachus tigerinus, dark green = Euphlyctis cyanophylyctis, orange = Megophrys (Xenophrys) zhangi, red = Microhyla ornata. Reptiles: light purple = Calotes versicolor, light blue = Hemidactylus platyurus, dark blue = Hemidactylus frenatus, dark purple = Herpetoreas platyceps." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3670116" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3670116/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">Figure 1</figureCitation>
). Males were always encountered while calling, usually from under grass, about onehalf metre from the water (
<figureCitation box="[493,594,1445,1469]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="8.[160,225,998,1021]" captionTargetBox="[354,962,142,966]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[354,962,142,966]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 3. Additional amphibian species observed during this survey. (a) Hoplobatrachus tigerinus, (b) Hoplobatrachus tigerinus, (c) Euphlyctis cyanophylyctis, (d) male Megophrys zhangi, (e) female (left) and male (right) of Megophrys zhangi, (f) tadpole of Megophrys zhangi, (g) male Megophrys zhangi calling on artificial substrate near water feature, (h) Microhyla ornata." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3670120" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3670120/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">Figure 3</figureCitation>
(h)). Larvae were usually present in large numbers in the water sources around which adults were calling. Recent work suggests that 
<collectingCountry box="[217,284,1514,1538]" name="Nepal" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">Nepal</collectingCountry>
contains multiple species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tschudi" authorityYear="1838" box="[640,750,1514,1538]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Microhyla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[640,750,1514,1538]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">Microhyla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and that the specimens encountered around KTM may belong to a related species, rather than 
<taxonomicName authority="(Khatiwada et al. 2017)" baseAuthorityName="Khatiwada" baseAuthorityYear="2017" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Microhyla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ornata">
<emphasis box="[907,1018,1549,1573]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">M. ornata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Khatiwada JR &amp; Shu GC &amp; Wang SH &amp; Thapa A &amp; Wang B &amp; Jiang J" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431" pagination="221 - 239" refId="ref7163" refString="Khatiwada JR, Shu GC, Wang SH, Thapa A, Wang B, Jiang J. 2017. A new species of the genus Microhyla (Anura: Microhylidae) from Eastern Nepal. Zootaxa. 4254: 221 - 239. doi: 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4254.2" type="journal article" year="2017">Khatiwada et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Molecular sequencing or in-depth morphological analysis would help resolve the taxonomic position of KTM 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tschudi" authorityYear="1838" box="[626,736,1618,1642]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Microhyla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[626,736,1618,1642]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">Microhyla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Because we only encountered this species outside of national parks, we were unable to conduct further analyses (
<figureCitation box="[168,265,1688,1712]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="2.[160,225,1557,1580]" captionTargetBox="[164,1152,691,1526]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[163,1153,690,1526]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figure 1. Map showing distributions of species surveyed in the Kathmandu Valley: circles = amphibians, squares = reptiles. Colours are defined as follows, amphibians: dark blue = Duttaphrynus melanostictus, purple = Nanorana liebigii, yellow = Fejervarya syhadrensis, light green = Hoplobatrachus tigerinus, dark green = Euphlyctis cyanophylyctis, orange = Megophrys (Xenophrys) zhangi, red = Microhyla ornata. Reptiles: light purple = Calotes versicolor, light blue = Hemidactylus platyurus, dark blue = Hemidactylus frenatus, dark purple = Herpetoreas platyceps." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3670116" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3670116/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="1431">Figure 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
